    Homework #6: Willow Sort My Items For Me?
    (Comparables and Comparators)

    Willow is a distant (non-existent) cousin to "Zillow", a real-estate company. A Willow object is a real-estate property. Willow's main clients are UVa students looking to rent an apartment or house for the academic year.
    College students look for a lot of things when it comes to real-estate; however, it can be boiled down to five main things:
    (1) neighborhood (the neighborhood the property is in: a String - e.g. "JPA")
    (2) bedrooms (the number of bedrooms in the property: an int - e.g. 2)
    (3) garage (if the property has a garage or not: a boolean - e.g. true or false)
    (4) distToCenter (the distance to the center of grounds: a double - e.g. 0.45 miles)
    (5) price (the rent of the property per month: a double - e.g. $1000.00)

    Each academic year students search for the best property for them. Over the years Willow learned what aspects of each property were appealing for students, and started producing real-estate property listings for students to look at. Willow discovered three (3) popular ways students prioritize property searches:
    WAY #1: {"Typical" prioritization for property searches - "natural ordering of properties"}
    - Sort first by price (sorting cheaper properties before more expensive properties),
    - then by distance to the center of grounds (sorting properties closer to the center of grounds before properties further away.)
    WAY #2: {"Prioritizing bedrooms and garage"}
    - Sort first by the number of bedrooms (sorting properties with more bedrooms before properties with less bedrooms)
    - then by garage (sorting properties that have a garage before properties that don't have a garage.)
    WAY #3: {"High-end Search"}
    - Sort first by neighborhood (sorting in ascending order),
    - then by price (sorting more expensive properties before less expensive properties)


    ** What you need to do:
    In the Willow class, implement the Comparable interface and write the following methods (see Javadoc for details):
    - non-default constructor that takes in all the class fields
    - compareTo() method that sorts properties in the "typical"/"natural" way (WAY #1)
    - sortByNaturalOrdering() method
    - sortByBedroomsAndGarage() method
    - sortByNeighborhoodAndPrice() method
    - toString() method (write this in the way we have given) - getters and setters for all class fields (use appropriate naming conventions)

    Then write two (2) separate classes (in the same Jave Project):
    - CmpByBedroomsAndGarage: that implements the Comparator interface. Write a compare() method in this class that sorts properties by WAY #2.
    - CmpByneighborhoodAndPrice: that implements the Comparator interface. Write a compare() method in this class that sorts properties by WAY #3.


    ** Testing:
    You will need to test your code by writing JUnit tests. (You will submit this to Web-CAT too.)
    You will need to write at least two (2) JUnit tests (using JUnit 4) for each of the following methods:
    - the Willow constructor
    - compareTo() in Willow (which also tests the sortByNaturalOrdering() method)
    - compare(Willow p1, Willow p2) in CmpByBedroomsAndGarage (which also tests the sortByBedroomsAndGarage() method)
    - compare(Willow p1, Willow p2) in CmpByNeighborhoodAndPrice (which also tests the sortByNeighborhoodAndPrice() method)
    You are encouraged to perform main-method testing as well to quickly test your code.


    ** Submitting:
    Submit the following files on Web-CAT by the due date:
    1) Willow.java
    2) CmpByBedroomsAndGarage.java
    3) CmpByNeighborhoodAndPrice.java
    4) Your JUnit test file as HW6Tests.java

    You have unlimited submissions to Web-CAT for this homework assignment.
    Remember to review the Javadocs to ensure that the names of all methods and fields (including capitalization) matches.
    Also make sure you do not submit the .class files!


    ** Commenting/Style:
    - Use correct naming conventions, including appropriate camelCasing and TitleCasing
    - Comment each file, with a block at the top of the file denoting assignment information and comments for each field and method of your classes. You should also comment portions of yourcode that may be difficult to follow. We would like you to get into the habit of commentingyour code. This adds to the readability of your code which contributes to “good quality” code.
    - Do not put your classes into a package (leave it as "default") - if in doubt, ask your TA or professor
